Diagnosis.— Males of
E. chitina
are characterised by the embolic loop enlarging ectally (
Fig. 9
), the tip of embolus (E) coming out of the tegular apophysis ( TEGA sensu
Bennett 2005
) at a right angle (
Figs 9–10
), a palpal tibia rather long and thin (
Fig. 9
), a non­RTA palpal tibial apophysis ( sensu
Bennett 2005
) with two small and elongate ctenidia (CT) (
Fig. 11
). Females are characterised by the carinate lateral fovea forming a broad median septum (MS) slightly narrowing anteriorly (
Fig. 12
), a shallow and inconspicuous atrium (AT) with two small rounded spermathecae (S) touching medially, not always visible through the cuticle (
Fig. 12
), and fertilisation ducts (FD) originating apically from the spermathecae (S) (
Fig. 13
).
